<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><soap:Envelope xmlns:soap="http://www.w3.org/2003/05/soap-envelope" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema"><soap:Body><SearchMessageTranslationsResponse xmlns="http://cityindex.co.uk/MessageTranslation"><SearchMessageTranslationsResult><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternCommonDoji_calculation</k><v>First, the body height of the candle is tested to be equal-to or less-than the first parameter. Second, the total height is tested to be greater-than or equal-to the second parameter. If both conditions are met, the doji is identified.</v><desc /><id>983</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternDragonflyDoji_calculation</k><v>First, the body height of the candle is tested to be equal-to or less-than the first parameter. Second, the total height is tested to be greater-than or equal-to the second parameter. Third, the open and close values are both tested to equal the high value. If these conditions are met, the dragonfly is identified.</v><desc /><id>987</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternGravestoneDoji_calculation</k><v>First, the body height of the candle is tested to be equal-to or less-than the first parameter. Second, the total height is tested to be greater-than or equal-to the second parameter. Third, the open and close values are both tested to equal the low value. If these conditions are met, the gravestone is identified.</v><desc /><id>991</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternHammer_calculation</k><v>First, the body height of the candle is tested to be equal-to or greater-than the first parameter. Second, the total height is tested to be at least twice the height of the body of the candle. Third, the close value is tested to equal the high value. If these conditions are met, the hammer is identified.</v><desc /><id>995</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternHangingMan_calculation</k><v>First, the body height of the candle is tested to be equal-to or greater-than the first parameter. Second, the total height is tested to be at least twice the height of the body of the candle. Third, the open value is tested to equal the high value. If these conditions are met, the hangman is identified.</v><desc /><id>999</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternHarami_calculation</k><v>First, the candle's high is tested to be lower than the higher of the previous candle's open or close. Second, the candle's low is tested to be greater than the lower of the previous candle's open or close. If both these conditions are met, we identify the harami or 'pregnant' candle formation.</v><desc /><id>1003</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternInvertedHammer_calculation</k><v>First, the body height of the candle is tested to be equal-to or greater-than the first parameter. Second, the total height is tested to be at least twice the height of the body of the candle. Third, the open value is tested to equal the low value. If these conditions are met, the inverted hammer is identified.</v><desc /><id>1007</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternShootingStar_calculation</k><v>First, the body height of the candle is tested to be equal-to or greater-than the first parameter. Second, the total height is tested to be at least twice the height of the body of the candle. Third, the close value is tested to equal the low value. If these conditions are met, the shooting star is identified.</v><desc /><id>1011</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternThreeBlackSoldiers_calculation</k><v>First, the three candles are all verified to be 'stepping down', all closing lower than opening. Second, the candle's are tested to have candle heights greater-than or equal-to the minimum soldier height specified. If both these conditions are met, the soldiers are identified.</v><desc /><id>1015</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternThreeWhiteSoldiers_calculation</k><v>First, the three candles are all verified to be 'stepping up', all closing higher than opening. Second, the candle's are tested to have candle heights greater-than or equal-to the minimum soldier height specified. If both these conditions are met, the soldiers are identified.</v><desc /><id>1019</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>ToolTipCurrentPrice</k><v>Shows the latest price for the market.</v><desc /><id>6462</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>latest_headlines</k><v>latest headlines</v><desc /><id>14328</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>BackTestAllowed</k><v>False</v><desc>Turns on back testing in AT</desc><id>14378</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>shell_browser_headerText</k><v>Unfortunately, the company tab is not supported by [your-browser], and you may not be able to see your live margin level or P&L.
In order to get up-to-date margin information, you can either <a href="[browser-link]" target="_blank">update your browser to the latest version</a>, or <a href="https://ciapi.cityindex.com/Download/MarginLive/Marginlivesetup.exe" target="_blank">download our Margin Live widget</a>.</v><desc>IFE Lite|This KVP is used to provide the header text of the oldIE page.</desc><id>16108</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>openPos_col_currentPrice_tooltip</k><v>Shows the latest price at which you can close your position.</v><desc /><id>18110</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>cic_error_getting_instrument_latest_activity</k><v>Error getting instrument latest activity</v><desc /><id>19393</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>cic_latest_activity</k><v>Latest Activity</v><desc /><id>19549</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>cic_test_order</k><v>Test Order</v><desc /><id>19622</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>testKey</k><v>testValue</v><desc>testDescription</desc><id>29424</id></msg_tr_ovrd><msg_tr_ovrd><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>key</k><v>testValue</v><desc>testDescription</desc><id>29425</id></msg_tr_ovrd></SearchMessageTranslationsResult></SearchMessageTranslationsResponse></soap:Body></soap:Envelope>

</desc><id>16137</id><ao_id>2377</ao_id></msg_tr><msg_tr><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>FLEXITP_CSSEDITOR_DESC</k><v>Look & Feel Editor\n
This tool allows you to update the look and feel of the platform by changing the colours displayed. \n

You can change the colours by performing the following steps:\n

1. Select a row that contains a colour that you want to update\n

When you do this, you will see a description of what elements relate to the colour.\n

2. Use the "New Colour Value" column to update the colour\n

In the "New Colour" column you are provided with a colour picker and a textbox containing the code for the associated colour.\n

Click on the colour picker and select the colour you prefer.\n

Where there are 2 colours, this simply means that the update relates to a gradient colour.\n

3. Click the "Apply" button to apply your changes to your current session.\n

This will update the colours of the IFE in your current session and refresh your layout to the default. If using a layout other than the default please ensure that you have saved your changes.\n

4. Click the "Save & Close" button to save your changes for future sessions.\n

If you do not click this whilst editing the CSS, then all changes will be lost.\n

5. Click the "Close" button to close the CSS window\n

You will be prompted to save any changes that you have made to ensure that you do not lose any updates accidentally. \n

6. If you want to revert back to the default colours for the platform, click the "Restore Default Values" button.\n

This will revert the site back to the default colours. \n

Help: If you wish to see this information again, simply click the "Help" button. </v><desc>Text collections.name: CityIndex.TradingAPI
collections.description:
The first part of the CIAPI uses the software architecture style of Representational State Transfer (REST). This is one of the standard web service methods to communicate over the internet with remote servers.

The CIAPI RESTful implementation uses the Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTPS) for communication between our back-end and your trading solution (client UI application). Request / response calls initiated by the client UI application must follow a simplified RESTful pattern supporting GET and POST, and encoding data in JavaScript object notation (JSON).

Typically, requests for information such as: available markets, historical prices, and account history are exposed via HTTPS GET requests. Requests that change state such as: placing a trade or logging on are performed using HTTPS POST.

requests.name: ListStopLimitOrderHistory
requests.description:
Queries the stop / limit order history for a specified trading account. The result set includes only orders that were originally stop / limit orders that currently have one of the following statuses (3 - Open, 4 - Cancelled, 5 - Rejected, 9 - Closed, 10 - Red Card). There is currently no corresponding GetStopLimitOrderHistory (as with ListActiveStopLimitOrders).
 
Notes on Parameters
ClientAccountId - this can be passed in order to retrieve all information on all trading accounts for which it is the parent. TradingAccountId - this can be passed to retrieve information specific to a certain trading account (the child of ClientAccount).
If neither ClientAccountId nor TradingAccountId is passed, then the information returned by default from the API is ClientAccount.

Return Value
ListStopLimitOrderHistoryResponseDTO

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the historical price ticks in JSON format.

requests.name: ListActiveStopLimitOrders
requests.description:
Queries for a specified trading account's active stop / limit orders.
This URI is intended to support a grid in a UI. One usage pattern is to subscribe to streaming orders, call this for the initial data to display in the grid, then call the HTTP service GetActiveStopLimitOrder when you get updates on the order stream to get the updated data in this format.
 
Notes on Parameters
ClientAccountId - this can be passed in order to retrieve all information on all trading accounts for which it is the parent. TradingAccountId - this can be passed to retrieve information specific to a certain trading account (the child of ClientAccount).
If neither ClientAccountId nor TradingAccountId is passed, then the information returned by default from the API is ClientAccount.

Return Value

responses.text:
{"NewsDetail":{"Story":"    TAIPEI, May 23 (Reuters) - Taiwan will launch futures 
contracts for trading on the island of benchmark stock indices 
from the U.S. and India, a senior Taiwanese securities official 
said on Monday.  
    The Taiwan Futures Exchange is planning a futures contract 
for India's Nifty 50  .NSEI  by the end of this year at the 
earliest or the first half of 2017, Tsai Shih-chuan, vice 
president of the Taiwan Futures Exchange, told Reuters on the 
sidelines of an exchange event.     
    Tsai said the plans are to launch futures on the DJIA  .DJI  
and S&P 500  .SPX  at the end of 2017 at the earliest. 
    "The one for India will be faster...but the issue of time 
difference has to be resolved on (the contracts for) U.S. 
stocks," Tsai said.  
    The move is aimed at expanding Taiwan's futures market and 
attracting foreign investors, he said. 
    Last year, the island's futures exchange launched trading in 
Japan's TOPIX, so far the only foreign equity index futures 
traded in Taiwan.  
 
 (Reporting by Roger Tung; Writing by J.R. Wu; Editing by Sam 
Holmes) 
 ((jr.wu@thomsonreuters.com; +886 2 2500 4881; Reuters 
Messaging: jr.wu.thomsonreuters.com@reuters.net)) 
 
Keywords: TAIWAN FUTURES/  
     
","StoryId":423604,"Headline":"Taiwan to launch futures contracts for U.S, India benchmark indexes","PublishDate":"/Date(1463984685000)/"}}

requests.name: GetActiveStopLimitOrder
requests.description:
Queries for an active stop limit order with a specified order ID. It returns a null value if the order doesn't exist, or is not an active stop limit order.
This URI is intended to support a grid in a UI. One usage pattern is to subscribe to streaming orders, call the HTTP service ListActiveStopLimitOrders for the initial data to display in the grid, and call this URI when you receive updates on the order stream to get the updated data in this format. For a more comprehensive order response, see the HTTP service GetOrder.

Return Value
GetActiveStopLimitOrderResponseDTO
 
Example

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment queries the active order with ID = 123456. HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the order query result in JSON format (GetActiveStopLimitOrderResponseDTO).

requests.description:

{"NewsDetail":{"Story":"    TAIPEI, May 23 (Reuters) - Taiwan will launch futures 
contracts for trading on the island of benchmark stock indices 
from the U.S. and India, a senior Taiwanese securities official 
said on Monday.  
    The Taiwan Futures Exchange is planning a futures contract 
for India's Nifty 50  .NSEI  by the end of this year at the 
earliest or the first half of 2017, Tsai Shih-chuan, vice 
president of the Taiwan Futures Exchange, told Reuters on the 
sidelines of an exchange event.     
    Tsai said the plans are to launch futures on the DJIA  .DJI  
and S&P 500  .SPX  at the end of 2017 at the earliest. 
    "The one for India will be faster...but the issue of time 
difference has to be resolved on (the contracts for) U.S. 
stocks," Tsai said.  
    The move is aimed at expanding Taiwan's futures market and 
attracting foreign investors, he said. 
    Last year, the island's futures exchange launched trading in 
Japan's TOPIX, so far the only foreign equity index futures 
traded in Taiwan.  
 
 (Reporting by Roger Tung; Writing by J.R. Wu; Editing by Sam 
Holmes)

requests.name: GetPriceBars
requests.description:
Get historic price bars for the specified market in OHLC (open, high, low, close) format, suitable for plotting in candlestick charts. Returns price bars in ascending order up to the current time. When there are no prices for a particular time period, no price bar is returned. Thus, it can appear that the array of price bars has "gaps", i.e. the gap between the date & time of each price bar might not be equal to interval x span.

Sample Urls:

    /market/1234/history?interval=MINUTE&span=15&PriceBars=180
    /market/735/history?interval=HOUR&span=1&PriceBars=240
    /market/1577/history?interval=DAY&span=1&PriceBars=10
    
Parameters

        MarketId 	string 	The ID of the market.
        interval 	string 	The pricebar interval.
        span 	    integer The number of each interval per pricebar.
        PriceBars 	integer The total number of price bars to return. 
        priceType 	string 	The price type being requested. If left blank then the default setting returns the MID price. Possible values are: ASK, MID, BID.
        
The following request to the Live CIAPI environment retrieves the 20 most recent 15 minute Bid price bars for the Wall Street CFD market (Market ID = 99498). HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

requests.name: SearchWithTags GTS
requests.description:
Returns a list of markets that meet the search criteria. This search extends ListMarketSearch by optionally searching within a specified market tag and only returning matching markets from the specified tag. Leave the query string empty to return all markets available to the user. The results contain the summarised MarketId and MarketName properties.

The market tag is optional and if not used, then this service call will behave the same as ListMarketSearch. The list of market tag IDs are provided in the table at Market Tag IDs.

Note: when searching for currency markets by name enter the format as "USD JPY" or "GBP USD". Do not use the "/" in the name of the currency pair.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment searches for markets with names matching the query string "Gold" within the "Commodities" market tag (96), and returns the first ten results.
HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the search results in JSON format (MarketInformationSearchWithTagsResponseDTO).

requests.name: ChangePassword
requests.description:
Change a user's password.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment changes the DM123456 account password from "allsystemsgo" to "openthedoor".

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ApiSaveAccountInformationResponseDTO in JSON format.

headers.name: X-Px
headers.value: nc h0-s1146.p11-fra ( h0-s56.p6-lhr), nc h0-s56.p6-lhr ( origin)

requests.name: ListOpenPositions
requests.description:
Queries for a specified trading account's trades / open positions.
This URI is intended to support a grid in a UI. One usage pattern is to subscribe to streaming orders, call this for the initial data to display in the grid, then call the HTTP service GetOpenPosition when you get updates on the order stream to get the updated data in this format.
 
Notes on Parameters
ClientAccountId - this can be passed in order to retrieve all information on all trading accounts for which it is the parent. TradingAccountId - this can be passed to retrieve information specific to a certain trading account (the child of ClientAccount).
If neither ClientAccountId nor TradingAccountId is passed, then the information returned by default from the API is ClientAccount.

Return Value
ListOpenPositionsResponseDTO

In a GET request, the response will contain an entity corresponding to the requested resource. In a POST request the response will contain an entity describing or containing the result of the action.

requests.name: ListMarketInformation
requests.description:
Retrieve the Market Information for the markets in the specified list of market IDs.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment requests the market information for the markets in the following list:
UK 100 DFT (400616113)

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

requests.name: FullSearchWithTags
requests.description:
Returns a list of markets that meet the search criteria. This search extends ListMarketInformationSearch by optionally searching within a specified market tag and only returning matching markets from the specified tag. Leave the query string empty to return all markets available to the user. The results contain the full ApiMarketInformationDTO.

The market tag is optional and if not used, then this service call will behave the same as ListMarketInformationSearch. The list of market tag IDs are provided in the table at Market Tag IDs.

Note: when searching for currency markets by name enter the format as "USD JPY" or "GBP USD". Do not use the "/" in the name of the currency pair.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment searches for markets with names matching the query string "Gold" within the "Commodities" market tag (96), and returns the first ten results. The full market information is returned for all search results.
HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing market information for the search results in JSON format (FullMarketInformationSearchWithTagsResponseDTO).

requests.name: ListMarketSearchPaginated GTS
requests.description:
Returns a markets page containing a list of markets that meet the search criteria. The search can be performed by market code and/or market name, and can include CFDs and Spread Bet markets. This method differs from ListMarketSearch in that the returned results are paginated.

Note: when searching for currency markets by name enter the format as "USD JPY" or "GBP USD". Do not use the "/" in the name of the currency pair.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment searches for markets with names matching the query string "Gold" and returns the first 20 results. The results are shown as 5 markets per page starting from page 1.
HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the paginated search results in JSON format (ListMarketSearchPaginatedResponseDTO).

requests.name: CancelOrder
requests.description:
Cancel the specified order - the order can be a resting entry order or an attached closing order to an open position.

Return Value
ApiTradeOrderResponseDTO
 
Example

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment cancels the entry order with order ID 12345 for the trading account ABCD890.
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ApiTradeOrderResponseDTO in JSON format.
